      <data key="d5">Advances in high-density (HD) diffuse optical tomography (HD-DOT) promise to over- come long-standing performance limitations in classification of sparse functional near-infrared spectroscopy (fNIRS) signals, but their combined impact on single-trial brain decoding and gen- eralization remains largely unquan</data>
